<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-095-065 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 188 645</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  August 1991 v114 n2 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Package delivery can spur your business.(alternative methods ofdocument transmission)(includes related article on delivery costs)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rowh, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Parcel delivery services offer many organizations an effectivemeans of transmitting documents when fax, electronic mail or othermodes of communication are unavailable or less efficient.andO;Applications such as legal documents, multi-page documents, photosand original artwork, irregularly-sized documents or materialswith extensive graphics are often not candidates for faxtransmission because they require signatures or contain physicalcharacteristics facsimiles cannot reproduce.andP;  Package deliveryfirms impose no constraints on the size or shape of a document andcan provide faster turn-around time than the US Postal Service.andO;Package delivery firms can also specialize in methods of deliveryor in package size.andP;  These firms can afford to invest in suchcomplex equipment as automatic handling-sorting devices, bar-codescanners, computers and in-house line-haul equipment to providefast, reliable service.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Industry AnalysisParcel DeliveryManagement of EDPTransportationCustomer relations.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>